ison's Weblog", "source_native_id": "https://simonwillison.net/2026/May/15/qr-code-generator/#atom-everything", "source_policy": "public_official", "source_type": "primary_artifact", "summary_hint": "<p><strong>Tool:</strong> <a href=\"https://tools.simonwillison.net/qr-code-generator\">QR code generator</a></p>\n        <p>Claude helped me build this tool for creating QR codes, for both text/URLs and for connecting to WiFi networks.</p>\n<p><img alt=\"Screenshot of a QR code generator web form. Heading &quot;QR code generator&quot; with subtitle &quot;Create a scannable code for a URL, text, or WiFi network.&quot; A segmented toggle shows &quot;URL / text&quot; and &quot;WiFi&quot; with WiFi selected. Below are fields: &quot;Network name (SSID)&quot; with placeholder &quot;My WiFi&quot;; &quot;Password&quot; with placeholder &quot;Password&quot; and a blue &quot;Show&quot; link; &quot;Security&quot; dropdown set to &quot;WPA / WPA2 / WPA3 (most common)&quot;; an unchecked &quot;Hidden&quot; checkbox; helper text &quot;Not sure? Leave it on WPA / WPA2 / WPA3 \u2014 that covers almost every home WiFi network.&quot; Below that: &quot;Style&quot; dropdown set to &quot;Square&quot;, an unchecked &quot;Border&quot; checkbox, &quot;Size&quot; dropdown set to &quot;Medium&quot;, and a &quot;Color&quot; swatch showing black. At the bottom is a blue &quot;Generate QR code&quot; button.\" src=\"http", "title": "QR code generator", "topics": ["topic_code-generator"], "updated_at": null}
{"artifact_links": ["https://simonwillison.net/2026/May/14/not-so-locked-in"], "author_or_org": null, "canonical_url": "https://simonwillison.net/2026/May/14/not-so-locked-in", "collection_method": "rss_atom", "confidence": "high", "content_hash": "73d3e46531e49bf3", "dedup_key": "rss-guid:simonwillison-blog:https://simonwillison.net/2026/May/14/not-so-locked-in/#atom-everything", "event_id": "event_bcc5302d63f323a8", "evidence_type": "supported_fact", "excerpt": "<p>This <a href=\"https://simonwillison.net/2026/May/14/mitchell-hashimoto/\">Mitchell Hashimoto quote</a> about Bun migrating from Zig to Rust reminded me of a similar conversation I had at a conference last week.</p>\n<p>I was talking to someone who worked for a medium sized technology company with a pair of legacy/<a href=\"https://simonwillison.net/2018/Jul/17/mark-norman-francis/\">legendary</a> iPhone and Android apps.</p>\n<p>They told me they had just completed a coding-agent driven rewrite of both apps to React Native.</p>\n<p>I asked why they chose that, given that coding agents presumably drive down the cost of maintaining separate iPhone and Android apps.</p>\n<p>They said that React Native has improved a lot over the past few years and covered everything their apps needed to do.</p>\n<p>And... if it turned out to be the wrong decision, they could <strong>just port back to native</strong> in the future.</p>\n<p>Like Mitchell said:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Programming languages used to be LOCK IN, and they're increasingly not so.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n    <p>Tags: <a href=\"https://simonwillison.net/tags/react\">react</a>, <a href=\"https://simonwillison.net/tags/coding-agents\">coding-agents", "identifiers": {}, "inferred_entities": [], "item_type": "rss_atom_item", "novelty_score": 0.0, "published_at": "2026-05-14T22:53:49+00:00", "ranking_explanation": "", "raw_metadata": {}, "relevance_score": 0.0, "retrieved_at": "2026-05-15T22:23:33Z", "source_id": "simonwillison-blog", "source_name": "Simon Willison's Weblog", "source_native_id": "https://simonwillison.net/2026/May/14/not-so-locked-in/#atom-everything", "source_policy": "public_official", "source_type": "primary_artifact", "summary_hint": "<p>This <a href=\"https://simonwillison.net/2026/May/14/mitchell-hashimoto/\">Mitchell Hashimoto quote</a> about Bun migrating from Zig to Rust reminded me of a similar conversation I had at a conference last week.</p>\n<p>I was talking to someone who worked for a medium sized technology company with a pair of legacy/<a href=\"https://simonwillison.net/2018/Jul/17/mark-norman-francis/\">legendary</a> iPhone and Android apps.</p>\n<p>They told me they had just completed a coding-agent driven rewrite of both apps to React Native.</p>\n<p>I asked why they chose that, given that coding agents presumably drive down the cost of maintaining separate iPhone and Android apps.</p>\n<p>They said that React Native has improved a lot over the past few years and covered everything their apps needed to do.</p>\n<p>And... if it turned out to be the wrong decision, they could <strong>just port back to native</strong> in the future.</p>\n<p>Like Mitchell said:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Programming languages used to be LOCK IN, and they're increasingly not so.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n    <p>Tags: <a href=\"https://simonwillison.net/tags/react\">react</a>, <a href=\"https://simonwillison.net/tags/coding-agents\">coding-agents", "title": "Not so locked in any more", "topics": ["topic_not-locked-any-more"], "updated_at": null}
